<h1>Theme and Category Descriptions</h1>
<h2><strong>Theme 1: From the local to the global: Sociopolitical &amp; cultural dimensions of society</strong><br>
</h2>
<p>This theme explores the multidimensional nature of society at local and global levels of analysis. Courses in this theme area explore how societies function from looking at issues of governance at the municipal level to complex global interconnections and realities.&nbsp; Courses in this theme area are divided into seven main categories, listed below:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Globalization, world affairs &amp; immigration</strong><br>
    Courses in this category explore the following main topics: the sociopolitical aspects of globalization such as migration, conflict, international affairs and development; the globalization of markets as well as related aspects of finance and business management in interconnected global markets; and the cultural aspects of globalization such as the growing convergences in entertainment, arts, media, as well as international and cross-cultural expressions of cultural realities through music, visual arts, communication, etc. </li>
  <li><strong>Indigenous experiences &amp; realities</strong><br>
    This category of courses explores the worldviews and experiences of Aboriginal and Indigenous communities in Canada and internationally.&nbsp; Courses explore sociopolitical, cultural, economic, health and spiritual aspects of Indigenous societies and realities.&nbsp; Also included are courses about Indigenous governance, sustainable development, law and conflict resolution. </li>
  <li><strong>Canadian issues &amp; experiences</strong><br>
    This category includes courses where Canadian society is the emphasis.&nbsp; While other course offerings may include a discussion of Canadian realities, this group of courses explores specifically Canadian societal structures and issues (e.g. immigration), systems of governance, entrepreneurship, history and culture as well as issues of nationalism and what defines Canada as a nation.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>Governance &amp; policies</strong><br>
    Courses in this category explore theories and systems of governance, as well as social, economic and public policies.&nbsp; Some courses also offer comparative perspectives. Issues discussed include democracy, citizenship, leadership, civic engagement, Indigenous governance, media regulation, food security and labour relations. </li>
  <li><strong>The city environment</strong><br>
    This group of courses explores the social, political, cultural and environmental aspects of urban contexts.&nbsp; Sustainability, architecture, management of resources and neighbourhood disparities are examples of topics explored in this category of courses.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>Colonialism &amp; imperialism</strong><br>
    This category includes courses exploring international relations and North/South power dynamics focusing specifically on histories and contemporary realities of colonialism and imperialism.&nbsp; Through an examination of cultural forms (e.g. literature), tourism practices, and societal conflicts, these courses examine relations between colonial powers and colonized societies as well as the dynamics of anti-colonial and anti-imperial resistance. </li>
  <li><strong>Cultural identity, history &amp; expression</strong><br>
    The focus of these courses is on cultural expression across the world.&nbsp; The emphasis of courses is on how societies express their diversity through contemporary and historical cultural forms such as music, visual arts, entertainment, literature, fashion, performance, and modes of communication.&nbsp; Also included are courses focusing on specific regions or countries, excluding courses that are Canada-specific, which appear in a separate category (see above).<br></li></ol>
    <h2><strong>Theme 2: Understanding and transforming communities: Theories, interventions &amp; practices</strong><br>
    </h2>
    <p>This theme area examines communities and the dynamics of difference, diversity and issues of conflict, inequality and oppression.&nbsp; Also included are courses that seek to address some of these dynamics, through community development practices, or engaging with ethics, social responsibility and human rights. </li></ol>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Race/racism</strong><br>
        This category includes courses that explore the dynamics of race, ethnicity and racism as they play out in Canadian society as well as in other sociocultural contexts historically and in contemporary times.&nbsp; Emphasis is placed on how these dynamics intersect with class, gender and sexualities.&nbsp; Included are discussions of politics, philosophy, the arts, media and development. </li>
      <li><strong>Diversity, social Identity &amp; social inequality</strong><br>
        Courses in this category focus on issues of difference, diversity, oppression and social inequities as they manifest in media, popular culture, the arts, organizations, societal structures and institutions.&nbsp; An exploration of power relations as they play out across social identities are also included in these courses.&nbsp; </li>
      <li><strong>Social change, justice and transformation&nbsp;</strong> <br>
        Responding to issues of oppression and social inequities, the courses in this category focus on theories and practices related transforming societies towards justice.&nbsp; Included are courses that take into account frameworks of social justice, human rights, and inclusion. </li>
      <li><strong>Crime, violence &amp; crisis</strong><br>
        This group of courses tackles the issues of conflict and crime and examines underlying dynamics at the levels of families, communities and societies.&nbsp; The courses also address the structures and processes to address conflict and crime.&nbsp; Also included are courses that focus on understanding, managing and communicating about crises and disasters. </li>
      <li><strong>Community practice and education</strong><br>
        This category of courses provides practice theories, models and processes in response to issues of violence, public health concerns and issues of marginalization.&nbsp; The emphasis is on building and transforming communities through interventions focusing on development, outreach and education. </li>
      <li><strong>Ethics/Social responsibility/legal issues (excluding LAW courses)</strong><br>
        These courses address the social, political, environmental and philosophical implications of business, health programming, media and criminal justice systems.&nbsp; The emphasis is on issues of ethics and legality.&nbsp; LAW courses are not included in this group of courses and can be searched for separately using the &ldquo;subject&rdquo; search function.&nbsp; </li>
      <li><strong>Conflict resolution and management: Community and interpersonal&nbsp;</strong> <br>
        The courses included in this category provide concrete skills and a knowledge base to understand and engage in conflict resolution.&nbsp; Issues dealt with focus on interpersonal conflict and issues, micro to macro levels of advocacy, as well as dispute resolution.</li>
    </ol>
<h2>
  <strong>Theme 3: Engaging with the physical, natural and material world</strong></h2>
<p><strong> </strong>This theme turns its attention to the physical and natural aspects of the world we inhabit to explore its biological, physiological, and chemical compositions and constituents.&nbsp; Also included are discussions of the technological aspects of society. </p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>The natural environment &amp; sustainability&nbsp;</strong> <br>
    This category of courses explores the natural world including its various life forms, ecological make-up, and physical building blocks. Also included are courses that examine the relationship between the natural world and human health.&nbsp; Courses also explore the management aspects related to sustainability and how to create and maintain healthy environments.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>Technology</strong><br>
    This group of courses seeks to understand not only the technical aspects of working with information technology and computer sciences but also seeks to explore the sociocultural and economic implications of technology for our societies.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>The natural and physical sciences (courses not included elsewhere)</strong>&nbsp; <br>
    These courses focus on understanding scientific building blocks in the areas of biology, chemistry, and physics.&nbsp; These courses do not focus on specific environmental or health aspects or impacts, but provide general and comprehensive knowledge in the natural and physical sciences.&nbsp; </li>
</ol>
<h2><strong>Theme 4: Cultivating leadership: Professional, business and management skills development</strong></h2>
<p><strong> </strong>This theme area covers essential knowledge for students interested in building their professional competencies in oral and written communication, financial management and research.</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Public relations and professional communication</strong><br>
    Courses in this category focus on communication skills needed to effectively deliver oral presentations or write public documents as well as communicate in management settings and roles.&nbsp; Also included are language courses focusing on business communication skills.</li>
  <li><strong>Project management, business management and program development</strong><br>
    These courses provide students with management and program development skills in fields such as the creative industries, public health, the retail sector and tourism. </li>
  <li><strong>Entrepreneurship/Executive leadership</strong><br>
    Courses address topics such as working with human resources, the legal aspects of management, and setting up businesses, as well as developing entrepreneurial insights, opportunities and skills.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>Financial knowledge &amp; skills</strong><br>
    Courses in this category focus on building skills and knowledge in economics, finance and law as they relate specifically to business management and personal financial planning. </li>
  <li><strong>Research and analysis skills</strong><br>
    These courses cover a broad range of research and analysis skills from disciplines such as psychology, geography, public policy and administration, health studies, and criminology, among others.&nbsp; This group of courses includes discussions of working with statistics, qualitative analysis, program evaluation and geographic mapping. </li>
  <li><strong>Advertising &amp; Marketing</strong><br>
    This category includes courses that build skills and knowledge in the principles, ethics, theory and practice of marketing and advertising while also exploring their sociopolitical and cultural aspects.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>Conflict resolution and management: Business&nbsp;</strong> <br>
    Focusing specifically on business management situations, these courses provide skills and knowledge in conflict resolution, negotiation, and interpersonal communication, as well as understanding organizational dynamics. </li>
</ol>
<h2>
  <strong>Theme 5: Nourishing creativity: Art, media &amp; communication knowledge and skills&nbsp;</strong></h2>
<p><strong> </strong>This theme area focuses on the theory, history and skills underlying creative activities.&nbsp; Included are courses introducing students to art and media theory and history, the development of audiovisual communication skills as well as technical printing and design skills. </p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Art and media theories and history</strong><br>
    This group of courses explores the theories and history underlying cultural and art production.&nbsp; Courses explore the performing arts, literature, music and photography.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>The screen: Film/Cinema/Television</strong><br>
    Courses in this category focus on the development of knowledge and skills in all areas related to the art of the screen; courses focus on aspects related to development, production, design and management in the fields of film and television.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>Technical design, printing &amp; finishing skills</strong><br>
    These courses explore the design and production aspects of working with graphics and print media.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>Communication skills</strong><br>
    This group of courses focuses on building knowledge and skills in the area of communication which includes writing; audiovisual communication skills such as working with photography and sound; as well as courses exploring the uses of new media and electronic/digital technologies.&nbsp;</li>
  </ol>

<h2><strong>Theme 6: Human experiences: Mind, body and soul&nbsp;</strong></h2>
<p><strong> </strong>This theme area explores human experiences related to physical and mental health as well as spiritual growth and development.&nbsp; </p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Health, healthcare and human development&nbsp;</strong> <br>
    This group of courses explores human health and development including discussions of cognitive function, physiology, stress and sensory processes.&nbsp; Also discussed are areas related to the fields of healthcare and healthcare management.&nbsp; </li>
  <li><strong>Religion, spirituality and personal growth</strong>&nbsp; <br>
    This category includes courses that explore religion and spirituality as well as personal development, psychology and growth.&nbsp; Courses examine these experiences through discussions of philosophical questions, musical traditions and Indigenous approaches to health and healing. </li>
</ol>
